                <p>A shorter mortgage term is a fantastic option to lower interest. Usually, shortening your loan term will result in a higher interest rate. A higher interest rate and fewer years of payment will result in significant savings over the long haul.</p>
                <p>How does this work? Let's look at an instance. Let's say your loan is $200,000. If you took out a 30-year loan at a 3.5% interest rate, you'd be paying around $123,000 in interest throughout your loan. If you were to reduce the term by half, you'll be paying approximately $57,000 throughout your loan. That's an increase of $66,000, and it's not even accounting for the fact that a shorter term will provide the borrower with a lower interest rate and more savings.</p>
                <p>One thing you should know when considering reducing the length of your loan is that it could raise your monthly mortgage payment. But less of your payment will be used to pay interest, and the majority of it is used to pay down your loan balance. It lets you increase your equity and get your home paid off quicker.</p>

